{
  "response_text": "The cumulative number of female prey killed begins at zero across all simulation runs. During the initial phase spanning approximately the first 400 to 600 steps, the metric exhibits a steep, monotonic increase, with cumulative kill counts rising rapidly from zero to values between approximately 80 and 115. The rate of accumulation varies across runs, with some simulations reaching 100 cumulative kills by step 400 while others require up to step 600 to reach comparable levels.\n\nBetween approximately 600 and 1200 steps, the trajectories transition into plateau phases as the rate of increase diminishes substantially. By approximately 1000 to 1500 steps, nearly all simulations have stabilized at final cumulative values ranging from approximately 108 to 125, with most runs converging between 115 and 125. A subset of simulations plateaus at lower values near 108 to 112, while one simulation exhibits a delayed trajectory that does not begin its rapid ascent until approximately step 200 and plateaus near 118.\n\nAfter step 1200, the metric remains constant across all runs, indicating that accumulation of female kills effectively ceases. The final plateau values represent approximately 43 to 50 percent of the initial prey population of 250 agents, suggesting that hunting pressure under these parameter configurations (20 immortal foragers with food storage capability) results in the extirpation of nearly all female prey units from the system within the first 1000 to 1500 steps. The variation in plateau timing and final cumulative values reflects stochastic differences in spatial encounter rates and hunting success across the simulation ensemble."
}

